===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|asken|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|axian|āxian|lang=ang}}, {{term|ascian|āscian|to ask, inquire, seek for, demand, call, summon, examine, observe|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|aiskōnan||to ask, ask for|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|ayǝs-||to look for|lang=ine-pro}}.  Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|easkje||to require, postulate, demand|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|eisen||to demand, require|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|heischen||to demand|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|æske||to provoke|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|äska||to demand|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|искать||tr=iskat'|to seek, look for|lang=ru}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# To look for an [[answer]] to a [[question]] by [[speak]]ing.
# To [[approach]] someone to do something.

=====Usage notes=====
* This is a [[catenative]] verb that takes the ''to infinitive''. See [[Appendix:English catenative verbs]]
* Pronouncing ask as /æks/ is a common example of [[metathesis]] and a feature of some varieties of English, notably [[African American Vernacular English]] (AAVE).
* The action expressed by the verb ''[[ask]]'' can also be expressed by the noun-verb combination ''[[pose]] a [[question]]'' ([[confer]] the parallel in German between ''[[fragen]]'' and ''[[ein]]e [[Frage]] [[stellen]]'').

